@node ADMIN "Administration - [msqladmin]"
@{LINDENT 4}

Program is used to perform administrative operations on an @{B}mSQL@{UB}
database server. Such tasks include the creation of databases,
performing server shutdowns, etc. The available commands are:
@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Version@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Displays version and configuration information about the currently running server.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Statistics@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Displays server statistics.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Reload@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Forces the server to reload access information.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Shutdown@{UB} or @{B}Startup@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Terminate or startup the @{B}mSQL@{UB} server.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Create@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Creates a new database.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Drop@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Removes a database from the server. This will also delete all data contained in the database!
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Copy@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Copies the contents of the database specified into a newly
created database. This command provides a simple mechanism
for creating a backup copy of a data for use as a test or
development environment.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Move@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINDENT 8}@{PAR}
Renames an existing database. The data is not modified in any way.
@{LINDENT 4}@{LINE}@{LINE}
@{b}NOTE@{ub} - most administrative functions can only be executed by the user
specified in the run-time configuration as the admin user. They can also
only be executed from the host on which the server process is running
(e.g. you cannot shutdown a remote server process).

@endnode

@node IMPORT "Importing - [msqlimport]"

@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Import@{UB}@{FG TEXT}
@{PAR}@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
Loads a flat ASCII data file into an @{B}mSQL@{UB} database table. The file shoul'd be
formatted in the Comma Separated Values format (@{B}CSV@{UB}). The @{B}CSV@{UB} format uses a
comma to separate data fields and quotation marks to quote the individual values.
If a value contains a quotation mark, it is escaped by prefixing it with another
quotation mark. When passed through, each line of the text file will be
loaded as a row in the database table.
@{LINE}@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 0}

@endnode

@node EXPORT "Exporting - [msqlexport|msqldump]"

@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Dump@{UB}@{FG TEXT}
@{PAR}@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
Produces an ASCII text file containing valid SQL commands that will recreate
the table or database dumped when piped through the @{B}mSQL@{UB} monitor program.
The output will include all CREATE TABLE commands required to recreate
the table structures, CREATE INDEX commands to recreate the indices, and
INSERT commands to populate the tables with the data currently contained in
the tables. If sequences are defined on any of the tables being dumped, a
CREATE SEQUENCE command will be generated to ensure the sequence is reset
to its current value.@{LINE}

@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Export@{UB}@{FG TEXT}
@{PAR}@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
Produces an Comma Separated Values (@{B}CSV@{UB}) export of the data from the specified
table. The @{B}CSV@{UB} format uses a comma to separate data fields and quotation marks
to quote the individual values. If a value contains a quotation mark, it is
escaped by prefixing it with another quotation mark. The output produced can
be used as input to other programs such as spreadsheets.
@{LINE}@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 0}

@endnode

@node SHOW "Informing - [relshow]"

@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Show @{UB}@{FG TEXT}
@{PAR}@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
It is used to display the structure of the contents of @{B}mSQL@{UB} databases. If no
arguments are given, it will list the names of the databases currently defined.
If a database name is given it will list the tables defined in that database.
If a relation is also given then it will display the structure of the table
(i.e. field names, types, lengths etc).@{LINE}@{LINE}
If an index name is provided along with the database and relation, it will
display the structure of the specified index including the type of index and
the fields that comprise the index. Else if sequence is provided along with
the database and relation, it will display details of the table sequence.
@{LINE}@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 0}

@endnode

@node QUERY "Monitoring - [msql]"

@{JLEFT}@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}Query@{UB}@{FG TEXT}
@{PAR}@{LINDENT 8}@{LINE}
The @{B}mSQL@{UB} monitor is an interactive interface to the @{B}mSQL@{UB} server. It allows you to
submit SQL commands directly to the server. Any valid @{B}mSQL@{UB} syntax can be entered
at the prompt provided by the @{B}mSQL@{UB} monitor. For example, by typing a "create
table" clause at the @{B}mSQL@{UB} monitor prompt you can instruct the database server to
create the specified table. The @{B}mSQL@{UB} monitor is intended to be used as a
mechanism for creating your database tables and for submitting ad-hoc SQL queries
to the server. It is not intended to be used for client application development
other than for testing queries before they are coded into your applications.@{LINE}@{LINE}
@{B}Control of the monitor@{UB} itself is provided by four internal commands. Each command
is comprised of a backslash followed by a single character. The available commands are:
@{PAR}@{LINDENT 16}@{LINE}
\\q@{TAB}@{B}Quit@{UB}@{TAB}@{I}(also achieved by entering Control-D) @{UI}@{LINE}
\\g@{TAB}@{B}Go@{UB}@{TAB}@{I}(Send the query to the server) @{UI}@{LINE}
\\e@{TAB}@{B}Edit@{UB}@{TAB}@{I}(Edit the previous query) @{UI}@{LINE}
\\p@{TAB}@{B}Print@{UB}@{TAB}@{I}(Print the query buffer) @{UI}@{LINE}

@endnode

